    "pages": 2,
    "content": "7 Week three: press to dictate This session will help players: • work on when and how to press • improve their ability to apply pressure to the player on the ball • dictate the direction of the player in possession. Coaching points • Once a goal is scored or the ball goes out of play in the 1v1 and 2v2 practices, ensure the next set of players go into the middle. The original attackers and defenders go off the pitch and swap roles for their next turn. • Ask players to think about their positioning and angle of approach when pressing. Doing this well can help players dictate what their opponent does next. For example, forcing a player out wide in the first activity can direct them out of play or towards the side goals which are worth less than the middle goal. Arrival activity • Create 15x10-yard areas with three goals at each end for a 1v1 activity. • Have other pairs waiting outside. • The attacker receives the ball and goes for goal. • Scoring in the middle goal is worth five points, the two side goals are worth one point. • The defender can win the ball back and score too. • When a goal is scored, the two players leave, and a new attacker and defender take to the pitch. • The ball gets played to the attacker to start the 1v1 battle. • Meanwhile, the original attacker and defender swap roles the next time they play. Practice one • Remove the goals from the first activity for this 2v2 practice. • Players look to beat their opponents and dribble past the end line to score. 8 Practice two • Create an area with a zone and a goal at each end. • Each team has a player in their own defensive zone while the rest are in the middle. • Players work together to score but can’t make a backwards pass to a teammate in the middle. • They can pass back to the player in their defensive zone."
